<br>
For some reason I doubt a lot of slasher armsmen are going slash just because the advantage in the Plains stage and Amethyst slash.  I think most of them just like the idea of swords.  Or I'm an arrogant fool(Which has been proven on my rant topic).<br>
<br>
Crushing has a short chain that keys off a block, which you should be doing a lot of.  There are 2 positionals, from which your 50 style keys of Side Crush.  Several very nice styles key off of the taunt style, which an armsman should be spamming in PvE.  Yeah, there is a lack of nice anytime styles.  Concussion is rather average, but the MoB is slowed a bit, i.e. more damage to them.  And you should be blocking so much that Skull Breaker could be nearly spammed.<br>
<br>
I doubt 90%f the armsmen and paladins I meet are using Scimitars for the tactical use(Longswords are a much, much better balance between speed and power).  They are just using Scimitars because they look badarse and make them think they're Sinbad.<br>
<br>
And trust me, we all know that armsmen are possibly the simplist class to play.  I've met armsmen at 44 on my minstrel that didn't know what intercept and protect did.  Armsmen do require to be constantly aware of what's around them and such, but Paladins need to keep track of their chants, Reavers need to keep track of their chants and make sure surge and their spells are working and mercs constantly need to stick and circle around the MoB to do positionals.  <br>
<br>
I have questioned a lot of armsmen in my guild about why they use slash, but very few had a legitimate answer.  Slash in Albion is even more common than Crush in Midgard, which is braggable.<br>
<br>
So what do my fellow mercs believe? Slash is a very viable spec, but no more viable than crush IMHO.  why is it we see so few crush specced armsmen and paladins?<br>
<br>
I am an arrogant fool.<br>
<br>
Peace,<br>
Joe <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#c0c0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/blighttanksofdaoc.showUserPublicProfile?gid=blame@lighttanksofdaoc>Blame</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://homepages.internet.lu/lordoftherings/images/boromir.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Determined Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 403<br> <font color=#000000>(6/1/03 11:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/flighttanksofdaocfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=249.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://homepages.internet.lu/lordoftherings/images/boromir.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Crush-Why the rarity?</span><hr size=1> I think it's for a lot of reasons, some of which are practical and some of which are just esthetic.<br>
<br>
Primarily, crush doesn't inspire many people. In SEVERANCE (I know I rant about this game all the time, but it's the standard of fun and versatility by which I judge every action game nowadays!) all cahracters have the option to carry blunt and bladed weapons, and, trust me, it's a lot less fun hitting somebody down with a staff than it is to chop their arms, leg and head off with a spear or an axe. Maybe people have an in-built instinct towards using something technologically advanced as a katana, rather than a stone club. It's also rahter bland, when you think of how varied the appearance and style can go. Sure, it'll be unique, but, well...<br>
<br>
Secondly, I think there's a role-player in all of us. And in literature/film, not many people use blunt weapons when they can cut stuff up. Skywalker, Aragorn, Robin Hood (yeah, picky, I know), the Knights of Camelot (see &quot;EXCALIBUR&quot;) all used swords. The sword speaks of versatility, tactical sharpness. The hammer speaks of brutality and thuggishness, as does the axe to an extent. However I know many of us are dirty violent axe-brawlers at heart <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    If flex weaponry had always been with us, was merc-compatible, crush-styled and wasn't considered a FoTM trinket, I think we'd have a lot more crush emrcs than we do.<br>
<br>
Tactically, crush has a reputation for being poor at PvE. This assumption is extended grotesquely in Albion, where the crush-vulnerable guys seem (at first) to be only Armsmen and Paladins, and the hammer looks at first sight to be only useful against things wearing a &quot;shell&quot;. Not a good thing.<br>
<br>
At RvR, crush is probably the best owing to its &quot;backseating&quot; for many peoples SC resist templates <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   However, the styles themselves are supposed to suck. Again, Slash seems to be Albions only useful anytime-spec.<br>
<br>
 And the armour-vuln/bonus tables show us the opposite anyway- -<br>
<br>
Crush is also neutral to Midgard (meaning you can't drop either a 'Zerker nor a thrust-vulnerable Healer as fast as you might want to), and gets penalties against the Champ, Warden and Hero, pretty popular classes.<br>
<br>
Compare this to Slash which gets bonus versus Norse Studded (which, it could be argued since the overpowering of LA, is the armour if Midgards primary tank force) AND the armour of the tanks in Hibernia.<br>
<br>
Anyway, thats my reasoning. Another thing is that when you're training as a Fighter, you're only given a training Sword. When you get to spec at level 2, you're wasting your points if you put them in Crush, because it's a style you can't get. Many players seem fine to settle into this mould nicely, and go slash after meeting their class trainer. Similar to Rogues with Thrust.<br>
<br>
^ I don't THINK you can go to a fighter trainer and get him to give you a crush weapon. Maybe you can. But I didn't find out how, and if other players didn't, then that could explain a few things <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
